strategy games are often conquer foe while time management goals are usually make enough money by doing work most effective manner unlike strategy games that are often focused on multiplayer gameplay time management games are single-player by nature time management games appeal different audience than general strategy games strategy games' primary audience considered be teen older males while time management audience considered be adult women game design typical time management game progression levels each which sets goal time limit for player level player would set priorities immediate actions for actors order satisfy appearing sub-goals that can be represented eg clients who want service planes that need land some games you can set queues up several consecutive actions actors will then do actions order set by player with their speed usually if action performed too late sub-goal failed goal level typically complete enough sub-goals within given time limit between levels players would upgrade their actors using game currency earned level eg make them move faster make clients wait longer before failing sub-goal serve more clients simultaneously settings themes typical setting for time management game puts player position some kind service worker some examples are waiter cook restaurant airport dispatcher office manager there are games with different settings art theme usually friendly cheerful simple common practice casual games typically game progresses through several 3-4 theme variations that represent different locations which represented by changes backgrounds appearance game objects examples time management games include airport mania diner dash delicious game series flight control kingdom chronicles references bateman chris beyond game design nine steps toward creating better videogames course technology ptr p isbn v t e video game genres list action beat 'em up o hack slash fighting maze o pac-man clone platform shooter o first-person o third-person o light g